  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "<!-- Please only use this template for submitting enhancement requests -->\r\n\r\n**What would you like to be added**:\r\nadd a flag in Azure auth module in kubectl to get AAD token with audience claim in proper (most commonly accepted) format.\r\n\r\n**Why is this needed**:\r\nThe original issue is explained very well in #86410. In sort, the current `azure` auth module will get a token whose `audience` claim has `spn:` prefix. This prefix is not documented in most Azure AD documentation which causes confusion and blocks some scenario.\r\n\r\nThere was an attempt to update existing `azure` auth module in #86412 which resulted in a breaking behavior to existing k8s clusters using Azure AD OIDC. The issue is documented well in #87464. Hence, the #86412 PR is reverted in #87507.\r\n\r\nAs discussed in [here](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/87464#issuecomment-577894188), a proper migration path to achieve #86410 with zero impact to existing clusters should be:\r\n1. (client side change) add a flag in azure auth module in kubectl to allow new behavior\r\n2. (server side change) update api server to support multiple `--oidc-client-id`\r\n3. customers can opt in to update `--oidc-client-id=spn:<guid>;<guid>` so that kubectl in old and new can still authenticate with api-server\r\n4. migrate kubectl/kubeconfig to use new flag\r\n5. update `--oidc-client-id=<guid>`\r\n\r\nThis issue is to implement the first task: **(client side change) add a flag in azure auth module in kubectl to allow new behavior**",
